ess with authorization2star  aAround 1 in 10 children born in the UK are fathered by men under the age of 25. These men are often from socially disadvantaged areas and frequently overlooked in both research and practice settings. Using findings from a major Economic and Social Research Council study, supplemented with additional data, the authors focus on the transitions of the young men into early parenthood and their unfolding lives thereafter. As negative popular and media discourse around young fathers begins to shift, policy makers, practitioners, researchers and students will find future policy and practice directions designed to nurture the potential of these young men and their children.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFatherhoodzGreat Britain. 0aFatherszGreat Britain. 0aTeenage fatherszGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aLadlow, With Linzi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTarrant, Anna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2024z978311129965540uhttps://doi.org/10.56687/9781447351726?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447351726423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447351726/original  a978-3-11-129965-5  Bristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2024b2024  aGBV-deGruyter-alles